**Mutating const Arrays**

**Key concept:**
const prevents reassigning the array reference, but you can still modify the array contents.

**What you CAN do:**
```javascript
const S = [5, 4, 3];
function mutateArray(){
    "use strict";
    S[0] = 2;  // Change element at index 0
    S[1] = 1;  // Change element at index 1
    S[2] = 0;  // Change element at index 2
}
mutateArray();
console.log(S); // [2, 1, 0]
```

**What you CANNOT do:**
```javascript
const S = [5, 4, 3];
// S = [1, 2, 3]; // This would cause an error
```

**Object mutation:**
```javascript
const mutateObj = {name: "Sam", age: 7};
mutateObj.age = 8;        // This works
mutateObj.name = "Sally"; // This works
console.log(mutateObj);   // {name: "Sally", age: 8}

// mutateObj = {name: "Bob"}; // This would cause an error
```

**To prevent mutation:**
Use `Object.freeze()` to make objects/arrays truly immutable.

